  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 삼구(三驅) : '
    value: 《주역》비괘(比卦)에, “왕의 삼구(三驅)를 하는데 앞에서 잡히는 것은 놓아 주자.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 박상(剝床) : '
    value: 눈앞에 다가오는 재앙을 말한 것임. 《주역》박괘(剝卦)에, “박상이부(剝床以膚)”라 하였고, 그 주에 상(床)은 사람의 안식하는 곳인데, 상이 박락(剝落)하게 되면 사람의 몸에 미치고 만다.” 하였다.
english:
  title: A Memorial Against the Royal Hunt
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant Hong Gwi-dal respectfully submits this memorial.

    Barbarians have troubled civilized lands since ancient times—this much was unavoidable. Yet never has the calamity been as severe as in these recent years. Within the past two years, the people of Pyongan and Hamgyong provinces have suffered death and capture without respite—some months witnessing two such incidents. The losses mount beyond counting. Most grievous is the recent raid by brigands at Sanyang, who in a single assault captured over a hundred souls and vanished as if into an unpeopled land, scattering our people like sheep before a wolf. One region lies entirely depleted. How could we imagine such things befalling a mighty court?

    Though border commanders prove unequal to their posts and defenses have been poorly maintained, this truly speaks of our nation's fate grown uncertain, calamity converging upon us from all sides, leaving our frontier people to bear the suffering. When wives dominate their husbands or barbarians vex civilized lands, these are extraordinary disturbances. Heaven sends such calamities to warn its rulers, to stir their hearts to vigilance, and to strengthen what they lack. Of late, thunder and hail have shown Heaven's displeasure within our realm, while barbarian raids threaten without. Heaven's love for Your Highness is made manifest in these warnings. What then must we do?

    Governor and subject, high and low must mutually admonish and correct one another. We must cultivate virtue and refine our governance, making it our foremost duty to dispel calamity and eliminate threats. Needless pursuits and non-urgent undertakings should be set aside entirely.

    The hunts of our ancient kings served to train martial valor and to present game to the ancestral temples—these cannot be abandoned. Yet should they become routine? When borders rest secure and all four quarters are peaceful, lest we grow complacent in safety, we conduct martial reviews and arrange such ceremonies. But when disaster looms before our eyes and peril threatens at our door, why cling to custom and persist in such non-urgent affairs?

    Now Rishan's soldiers and people—over a hundred captured, many killed—and two of our palace guards, one seized and one fallen. These commoners and elite soldiers are our charges, our very hands and claws. That they lie dead in foreign fields or enslaved in barbarian tents while we remain idle—could any parent hear this unmoved? How could we bear to pursue other matters?

    The barbarians have profited from our lands before, yet now their gain is multiplied a thousandfold. Seeing such success, they will surely marshal their forces and rise against us. The scourge will not end here. Our people who have fallen into captivity may think themselves fortunate merely to survive—what thought have they for honor? Among the hundred captured, surely some like Han Shih-chung or Aisan will emerge as guides for the enemy, bringing further ruin upon us. Who can say how many such traitors will arise? The thought chills my heart. The future calamities loom beyond description.

    This is the moment to lie upon thorns and taste gall, to gather strength and sharpen our resolve, to wait upon the hour and act decisively to wash away even a fraction of this shame and humiliation. Yet we concern ourselves with ceremony and spend days hunting mere miles from the capital. Is this wisdom?

    Some say: "Martial training strengthens the army—does it not serve border defense?" I must respectfully disagree. A grand review of veteran soldiers, instructed in the arts of advance and retreat, attack and parry—this might suffice. Yet if we dig the well only when parched, what relief can it bring? Now we employ merely the capital's garrison, supplemented by minor officials, attendants, and common folk. In name it is martial training; in truth it is mere hunting. How does this address any genuine emergency?

    Others say: "Hunting provides offerings for the ancestral temples and sustenance for the court—how can this be abandoned?" I would answer: those who now perish and are captured are all children of our former kings and queens. When these children fall to brigands and robbers, can their descendants offer sacrifice in good conscience while neglecting rescue? Would the spirits of our ancestors find peace in such offerings?

    Once Han Emperor Wen, that guardian of civil governance in an age of peace, ruled when no barbarian dared breach the frontier gates. Yet even then, Jia Yi wept bitterly and mourned for the empire. Had Jia Yi lived in these times and witnessed these events, what grief would possess him? This is precisely the hour when court and people should weep and wail, deepening virtue and strengthening governance. How could we occupy ourselves with lesser things?

    Moreover, Your Highness, in the wake of Emperor Seongjong's passing, observed mourning rites with excessive devotion, neglecting proper rest. From this arose the chill and fever that has plagued you these five or six years, requiring constant medication. Now you spend days abroad, laboring through dawn and dusk, exposed to frost and dew. Should any ailment strike you, how could we bear it?

    I believe the immediate course demands: First, issue a decree censuring your border commanders for their failure in defense, rousing them to dedicate themselves to new accomplishments. Second, issue an edict of sorrow to comfort the families of the slain and captured. Third, examine yourself closely, demonstrate reverence and caution, and see that your ministers do likewise—each cultivating their virtue and refining the administration, maintaining this resolve without wavering. Thus will the governance cultivated within our realm flourish, and the victories against external enemies will be achieved.

    If the royal hunts of the four seasons cannot be entirely forgone, then let it suffice to venture near the capital, conduct a single day's hunt, present the game to the ancestral temples and your household, and return. Thus might we preserve both duties.

    Your servant holds the lowly position of counsel and remonstrance. To withhold what I know would betray your grace. I dare submit this memorial at risk of my life, awaiting your judgment.
  footnotes:
    - 'Sanyang (山陽會): A location in the border region where a significant raid occurred.'
    - 'Han Shih-chung and Aisan: Historical examples of those who became guides or collaborators with invaders.'
    - 'Lying upon thorns and tasting gall (臥薪嘗膽): An allusion to the ancient king Goujian of Yue, who endured hardship to build strength for revenge—symbolizing steadfast determination in adversity.'
    - 'The ceremony of three drives (三驅): An ancient royal hunting ritual that balanced martial training with respect for game and the spirits.'
    - 'Peeling of the bed (剝床之災): A metaphor from the I Ching suggesting imminent catastrophe that spreads from external threats to internal collapse.'
